                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="216619" author="tappro" created="Mon, 18 Dec 2017 17:42:06 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;James, I see that each run in my local vm, so you may be right  about time gap. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="216612" author="simmonsja" created="Mon, 18 Dec 2017 17:14:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;So I attempted to reproduce the problem locally and I can&apos;t. It passes sanityn 32b. I have a theory why it fails. Using seconds is to large of a time gap. The pages are not being purged because the time that passes is less than one second. I bet if I move to nanoseconds this problem will go away.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="216603" author="bogl" created="Mon, 18 Dec 2017 16:14:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;suspect it may be due to time64_t being signed while cfs_time_t is unsigned&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="216602" author="simmonsja" created="Mon, 18 Dec 2017 16:12:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Oh that is strange. I will track down what the conflict is. Thanks.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="216594" author="pjones" created="Mon, 18 Dec 2017 15:51:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Should have been fixed by revert of offending patch&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="216571" author="tappro" created="Mon, 18 Dec 2017 08:06:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve done git bisect and it shows commit 4f2a5d5887492da9abe320074511811415e0a06c as source of problem. This is change &lt;a href=&quot;https://review.whamcloud.com/#/c/30063/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://review.whamcloud.com/#/c/30063/&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-9019&quot; title=&quot;Migrate lustre to standard 64 bit time kernel API&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-9019&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;LU-9019&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This change passed own tests so it seems that issue is result of interaction with some other patch, anyway, reverting of this particular patch solves the problem&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
